Why does lodash use an incredibly slow method for `_.isUndefined`?

``` js
function isUndefined(value) {
  return typeof value == 'undefined';
}
```

Is there a case when this function would not work properly?

``` js
function isUndefined(value) {
  return value === undefined;
}
```

This [jsPerf test](http://jsperf.com/lodash-isundefined-vs-triple-equals/6) shows that the method currently used is 2.7x slower than the method I'm suggesting.

```
var ary = [1, 2, 3];
var addOne = function(x) { return x + 1; };

// case (A)
_.takeWhile(_.map(ary, addOne), function(value, index, array) {
  console.log(array); // [2, 3, 4]
});

// case (B): use chaining
_.chain(ary).map(addOne).takeWhile(function(value, index, array) {
  console.log(array); // [1, 2, 3]
}).value();
```

The 3rd argument passed to callback at case (A) and the one at case (B) are different. I guess it is not an expected result at case (B).

But if we want to correct it (to pass `[2, 3, 4]` at case (B)) it cannot be evaluated lazily anymore because `[2, 3, 4]` cannot be got unless the _.map operation is entirely executed.
Personally I haven’t used this 3rd arg so I cannot imagine how it’s useful, but I think the advantage of lazy evaluating should be prior.

Same problem occurred when I was implementing the lazy version of `_.uniq` (#912). While my personal opinion is to obsolete this 3rd argument at some cases, I want to hear your opinion. Thank you.
